{\up #}{\footnote # HID_HOWTOEDITNODES}
{\up K}{\footnote K Edit Nodes}
{\plain\f16\fs20 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b Edit Nodes\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20 Node editing operations frequently use the toolbar buttons   All these buttons do different, though similar, actions depending on whether you are in Editing Boundary mode or in Editing Velocity mode (see }{\ul {\f80\fs20 Edit menu}}{\v menu_edit}{\plain\f80\fs20 )\par 
\par 
\{bmc FH330184.BMP\}
\par 
\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Pick or Update}{\plain\f80\fs20 :  Use this button to pick a new boundary for editing if you are editing boundary, or to pick a new velocity layer if you are editing velocity.  If it gets difficult to pick the right boundary, especially when complicated nodes clustered together, try to use mouse to click close to a particular node on that boundary, or use }{\ul {\f80\fs20 view}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80\fs20  to zoom up a smaller area to ease choosing. The selected boundary will be marked by a green solid line connecting blue nodes on that boundary, while other un-selected boundaries are marked by black lines connecting green nodes.  These nodes will not be connected for boundaries that have segments going out of the screen.  For picking a particular layer, you'll see that there are only two lines marking the upper and lower bounds of your selected layer   Since you can only select one such interface  to edit, this selected interface is marked by red line while the other by black line.  It can sometimes be tricky to pick the right interface of a particular layer in case of complicated model.  But you can always overcome this by (1) Choose nodes away from the clustered part but on the same interface, and click close to these nodes but within your desired layer (if you accidentally clicked close to the same node but from another adjacent layer, you will see different interfaces appear marking a different layer); (2)  use }{\ul {\f80\fs20 view}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80\fs20  to zoom up a smaller area to ease choosing.\par 
\par 
This button can also serve as updating your screen in case your screen does not update itself during some kinds of modeling editing operations.  Selecting }{\plain\f80\fs20\ul Pick or Update}{\plain\f80\fs20  button will remove the locking for re-painting the screen.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Delete Node}{\plain\f80\fs20 : Use this button to delete a boundary node or a velocity node.  Please node that SeisWide can not UNDO this action, so if you choose this tool, and click on a node, you have deleted that node permanently.  So be careful here and save your model frequently!\par 
\par 
After you have selected the }{\plain\f80\fs20\ul Delete Node}{\plain\f80\fs20  in velocity editing mode, please make sure you have selected the right interface (marked by red line) of the right layer before clicking anywhere inside the model. The program will react to your mouse clicks by looking for the most likely nodes to delete, even if your mouse click is \'93unrealistically\'94 far away from your selection.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Edit/Move Node:}{\plain\f80\fs20  Use this button to edit }{\plain\f80\fs20\b existing}{\plain\f80\fs20  nodes.  In boundary editing mode, this includes moving a node and the screen will stop re-painting even after other windows cover the SeisWide screen.  This is useful when you are editing your model overlain with a depth section, because it will be unnecessary to refresh the complicated screen for every mouse clicks.  In velocity editing mode, however, the screen has to be refreshed for any velocity change at the mouse clicks.  Clicking on any node will pop up a dialog box asking you to change the existing velocity value; The dialog box also includes other un-editable information: the layer number of your selection, and X and Y coordinates for mouse-up point in km.\par 
\par 
This button, and a following button }{\plain\f80\fs20\ul Add Node}{\plain\f80\fs20 , are also useful in knowing the velocity value of a node, and also for knowing the X and Y coordinates of a point in the screen (in fact, that is the only way by which you can know where exactly you have clicked your mouse in the velocity model).\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Add Node:}{\plain\f80\fs20  This button enables your mouse clicks to add nodes.  In boundary editing mode, mouse clicks on a selected boundary (marked by nodes turning blue from green) is followed by red points (which will be added nodes) with screen refreshing turned off.  In velocity editing mode, mouse clicks on a selected interface (marked by red line) of a layer are followed by a dialog box which asks you to change the velocity at those points.\par 
\par 
This button, and a preceding button }{\plain\f80\fs20\ul Edit Node}{\plain\f80\fs20 , are also useful in knowing the velocity value of a node, and also for knowing the X and Y coordinates of a point in the screen (in fact, that is the only way by which you can know where exactly you have clicked your mouse in the velocity model).\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Duplicate Boundary:}{\plain\f80\fs20  Only used in editting boundaries.  Clicking on it will pop up a message informing you that duplicated boundary will cover the existing selected one, making it visually difficult to distinquish between the two overlaped boundaries. You can select "Cancel" to cancel the operation.  This function is useful when you only want to add a layer in a small part of the model.  Remember that raytracing programs require that every boundary must extend from the leftmost to the rightmost of the model.  Therefore, you can duplicate a boundary and then move a few nodes on the new boundary to simulate inserting of a new layer.\par 
Note that after this duplication, the new boundary is automatically selected for you to edit, and try not to leave duplicated boundaries intact while saving the model to avoid visual ambiguity.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Insert Layer:}{\plain\f80\fs20   This button can only be used in velocity editing mode.  In that mode, first make sure you have selected a layer, then clicking this button will bring up a dialog box prompting average velocity for you to reference.  In most cases, you just need to click OK without changing anything here; you can always later change your model using other buttons.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Delete Layer:}{\plain\f80\fs20   Clicking this button prompts you to delete a selected boundary or a selected layer. Please node that SeisWide can not UNDO this action, so if you choose this tool, and click on a boundary or a layer, you have deleted that object permanently.  So be careful here and save your model frequently!\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul New Model:}{\plain\f80\fs20   Clicking this button will pop up a dialog box prompting you for information about a new velocity model.  If you click OK here, all existing velocity information in memory will be erased (your existing velocity file on disk will be ok, of course).  You specify number of layers (if not sure, just use default values; you can always add or delete later on), minimum and maximum distance (note: negative distance is not supported for modeling in SeisWide; minimum and maximum distance can not be changed later on within SeisWide although you can always output the model in Zelt\'92s ascii text format and change from there), and maximum depth for your model (Earth surface is always assumed to be at 0 km depth).  \par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Save Velocity:}{\plain\f80\fs20   Clicking this button will save the velocity information to existing file (make sure you have already set a file name in }{\plain\f80\fs20\ul Save Velocity as}{\plain\f80\fs20  or in the combined parameter list from the }{\ul {\f80\fs20 view}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80\fs20  menu).\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b\ul Save Velocity as:}{\plain\f80\fs20  Clicking this button will pop up a dialog box prompting for a file name to hold the velocity mode.  You can use BROWSE to select a name.  Note: use BROWSE to change directory from here is not a wise action, because you will change the }{\plain\f80\fs20\b current directory}{\plain\f80\fs20  for the active document, and if some of the parameters of this document are not associated with paths, the program may complain about not finding a particular file which it used to be able to find.\par 
\par 
There are two radio buttons to select from this dialog box.  SeisWide internal binary format represents the binary format that SeisWide adopts for storing velocity data.  The other radio button is for Zelt\'92s ascii format and on clicking OK the velocity data in this ascii format will be shown automatically to NotePad in front of your eyes.  You will notice that an extension of .IN is added to whatever file name you have specified.\par 
\par 
Also note that if you close your active document without saving its velocity data first, this data will be permanently lost, and the program provides no warning about this (SeisWide only detects and prompts any unsaved information for the active .SEI document before closing).\par 
\par 
