}\page \pard\plain\s2\sl240 {\up $}{\footnote $ Generate a Velocity Model}
{\up #}{\footnote # HID_HOWTOMODEL}
{\up K}{\footnote K Velocity Modeling}
{\plain\f16\fs20 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b Generate a Velocity Model\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20 If you want to generate a velocity model from an MCS reflection time section, it is extremely easy with SeisWide. Just follow these steps:\par 
}\par 
\pard\s2\li360\fi-360\sl240 {\plain\f80\fs20 }{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20 Choose "View, Velocity Model" to switch to velocity section. Give a name for your intended velocity model.  Click the corresponding icon in SeisWide to create a new model. Choose "Edit, Velocity Node" to switch to velocity editing mode. Change the velocity of first layer to be, for example, 1.5. Choose "Edit, Boundary Node" to switch to boundary editing mode. Drag down the seafloor to the maximum depth you can expect, and perform }{\plain\f80\fs20\i time-depth conversion}{\plain\f80\fs20 . Choose "View, Both Velocity and Depth" to switch to view model and depth section. If the sea bottom reflection is above the seafloor of your model, the sea bottom reflector is already at the correct depth.  Select the bottom boundary of first layer, edit the nodes according this reflector.\par 
}{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20 Repeat step one for second layer. Then for the third, and then fourth......}\par 
\pard\s2\sl240 {\plain\f80\fs20 \par 
For information on how to edit boundary and velocity nodes, see section }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Edit Nodes}}{\v HID_HOWTOEDITNODES}{\plain .\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20 To display a velocity model, select }{\ul {\f80\fs20 View menu}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80\fs20 , Velocity Color Map, or Velocity Contours which adds contours to the model.  For help on how to select the various parameters, see }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Display Seismic Sections}}{\v HID_HOWTODISP}{\plain\f80\fs20 .\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\i Time-depth conversion}{\plain\f80\fs20  is in the }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Processing}{\plain\f80\fs20  menu. Clicking this will pop up a dialog box with a few parameters, most of which are the same as you entered in }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Display Seismic Sections}}{\v HID_HOWTODISP}{\plain\f80\fs20 .  In most cases you should just use the defaults and not change them; this helps make sure that the files for time section, velocity model, and depth, and the view window are all consistent with what you have seen.  The only exception is the options for correcting spherical dispersion. Checking this gain the amplitude by the depth to the power of 2 (or other chosen values).  I found that if your reflection data is only brute or provisionally stacked, you need to set the power to 2 during conversion to avoid extremely weak energy at greater depths. However, if your Segy data is already migrated in time, you might not need any spherical correction at all.  Well, maybe not right: I occasionally use a power of 1 for some migrated section (given the excuse that there is energy losses during wave traveling)!\par 
\par 
\par 
Here is a sample Visual C++ routine to read the SeisWide binary velocity file:\par 
\tab CFile filev(velName, CFile::modeRead | CFile::typeBinary);\par 
\tab if(filev.Read(&velMod.ncont, 4) != 4) return(FALSE);\par 
\par 
\tab filev.Read(&velMod.nzed, (long)(velMod.ncont*4));\par 
\tab if(velMod.ncont>30)\par 
\tab \{\par 
\tab \tab AfxMessageBox("Too many layers in the velocity file, max 30");\par 
\tab \tab return FALSE;\par 
\tab \}\par 
\tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.ncont; icont++)\par 
\tab \tab for (j=0; j<velMod.nzed[icont]; j++) filev.Read(&velMod.xm[j][icont],4);\par 
\tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.ncont; icont++)\par 
\tab \tab for (j=0; j<velMod.nzed[icont]; j++) filev.Read(&velMod.zm[j][icont],4);\par 
\par 
\tab filev.Read(&velMod.nlayer, 4);\par 
\tab for (i=0; i<2; i++)\par 
\tab \tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.nlayer; icont++) \par 
\tab \tab \tab filev.Read(&velMod.nvel[icont][i], 4);\par 
\tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.nlayer; icont++)\par 
\tab \tab for (j=0; j<velMod.nvel[icont][0]; j++) filev.Read(&velMod.xvel[j][icont][0],4);\par 
\tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.nlayer; icont++)\par 
\tab \tab for (j=0; j<velMod.nvel[icont][0]; j++) filev.Read(&velMod.vf[j][icont][0],4);\par 
\par 
\tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.nlayer; icont++)\par 
\tab \tab for (j=0; j<velMod.nvel[icont][1]; j++) filev.Read(&velMod.xvel[j][icont][1],4);\par 
\tab for (icont=0; icont<velMod.nlayer; icont++)\par 
\tab \tab for (j=0; j<velMod.nvel[icont][1]; j++) filev.Read(&velMod.vf[j][icont][1],4);\par 
\tab filev.Close();\par 
\par 
Here is a sample fortran code for opening a SeisWide binary velocity file:\par 
\tab open(12,file='v.bin',status='unknown',form='binary')\par 
\tab write(12)ncont,(nzed(i),i=1,ncont)\par 
\tab write(12)((xm(icont,j),,j=1,nzed(icont)),icont=1,ncont)\par 
\tab write(12)((zm(icont,j),,j=1,nzed(icont)),icont=1,ncont)\par 
\tab write(12)nlayer,(nvel(i,1),i=1,nlayer),(nvel(i,2),i=1,nlayer)\par 
\tab write(12)((xvel(icont,j,1),j=1,nvel(icont,1)),icont=1,nlayer)\par 
\tab write(12)((vf(icont,j,1),j=1,nvel(icont,1)),icont=1,nlayer)\par 
