}{\plain Migrate to SeisWide with SEGY Data\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 You will need a seismic data in a format of industry standard, or a SEGY format.  This SEGY file must contain only one channel of data, as either a CDP-stacked section for reflection data, or a shot gather (or an OBS experiment) for non-zero offset and wide-angle data.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 If your Segy data was created in UNIX platform, you will need to convert it to a Windows/PC format if you haven't done so, before SeisWide can read it.  This is because of the fundamental difference of binary byte format the Unix and Windows/PC operating systems adopts.  There can be many ways to do this conversion.  I have successfully tested a shareware program "nscu" that runs on Unix on a SUN for this purpose.  This program can take many unix segy formats, among which the IBM Floating Point segy data have been tested to absolutely do the job.  Noteworthy is that the maximum length of each trace for this program is 20,000 samples in Unix version.  \par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 To convert your Unix Segy format to PC Segy format, follow these steps:\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 1. Transfer all four files in the NSCU directory to a directory in a SUN.\par 
}{\plain\fs20 Make sure you set the transfer mode to "binary".\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 2. Use "chmod +x nscu_UNX.exe" do the same thing for pcSegy.sh. \par 
}{\plain\fs20 This makes these two files executable.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 3. Type "pcSegy.sh FileNameUNIX.sgy FileNamePC.sgy" for the conversion.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 4. To know more about nscu program, type nscu_UNX.exe to see helps.\par 
}{\plain\fs20 Or expand all the source codes and documentation from nscu1.3.tar.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 5. Not sure if the same executable nscu_UNX.exe will work in other platform.\par 
