{\plain 
Pasting to Other Graphics Software\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 Any display in SeisWide can be directly put into most other graphics software in windows.  To do this, simply choose Edit Menu, Copy, or press Ctnl C, which will place the display onto windows clipboard.  You can open your favorate graphics editor such as CorelDraw, Lotus Freelance, MS-Word, MS Excell, MS Power Point et al. and paste by pressing Ctnl V.  If you prefer to edit individule details of SeisWide images, you could choose "Paste Special" in the "Edit" menu of these other softwares and choose to paste as "Metafiles".  A good news is that each seismic trace will be treated as one object so that CorelDraw, for example, would not complain about too many objects and works well with more than 1000 traces display at a good speed (if your PC is fast enough).  A bad news, however, is that CorelDraw 7.0 does not paste labels very well, especially if you paste as metafile instead of as SeisWide document, although CorelDraw 6.0 and 5.0 does not have this problem.  Of couse, you can always ungroup the pasted graphics (remove the labels by choose Edit, Display Tune-up in SeisWide) and delete all the unwanted stuff in CorelDraw.  But CorelDraw 7.0 still can not import the CGM metafile generated by rayplt.bat DOS program of SeisWide.  Again you can use MS-Excell or CorelDraw 6.0, 5.0 et al. to import and then paste to CorelDraw 7.0.\par 
\par 
While pasting SeisWide images onto other graphics editors can be easily executed by CNTL+C in SeisWide and CNTL+V in these editors, it can also be executed by choosing "Insert Object" of SeisWide from within those graphics editors.  You still do any drawings as usual in these editors.  If you double click a seismic section generated by SeisWide from within these editors, you will see SeisWide menus and you can change views from there.  When finished, just click outside the seismic section and everything becomes normal.  What a convenience!\par 
\par 
When you paste a color model into these graphics editors, better paste as SeisWide as opposed to metafile: because you will loose some color details in the metafile form.}\par\page \pard\plain\s2\sl240 {\up $}{\footnote $ Prev Pane Command}
