\plain\f80\fs20 Reduce huge Segy file into small file as you desire.  This operation can handle any large number of samples per trace in the input file, as long as the output file has <20000 samples per trace.}\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 \cell }\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 Coherency Mixing\cell Coherency mixing adjacent Segy traces. You can specify mixing range in km; however, when your mixing range is too great such that it covers >7 traces, the program will automatically use 7 traces for mixing. In specifying the "range of dips", I normally use 2, 9 (km/s) for refraction, and -9, 9 for reflection data. Coherency mixing can only be used if the distance/offsets always increase with trace number.}\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 \cell }\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 Time-Depth Conversion\cell Convert a near-offset time section into a depth section using a velocity model.  You can apply spherical correction to un-migrated time section (see }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Generate a Velocity Model}}{\v HID_HOWTOMODEL}{\plain\f80\fs20 ). For some shared parameter explanations see }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Display Seismic Sections}}{\v HID_HOWTODISP}{\plain ).}\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain \cell }\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain }{\plain\f80\fs20 Check Model Integrity\cell Check the current velocity model for errors.  If errors are found, a NotePad document will be shown instantly for you to investigate.}\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 \cell }\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 Ray Trace\cell Ray tracing using given ray parameter file, and velocity model file. It will evoke Collin Zelt\'92s raytracing program written in Fortran.}\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 \cell }\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 Ray Path\cell Simple, one-click display of ray path is not working.  However, after you run "Ray Trace", you can manually copy "p.out" file in your working directory to SeisWide program directory (typically c:\\Program Files\\Chian\\SeisWide) and run "rayplt.bat" to display the ray path and get a "test.cgm" file that holds the graphics. You could then use one of your favorate graphics editor (e.g. MS Word, Excell, CorelDraw, Freelance) to view and print it.}\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 \cell }\cell\pard\intbl\row\trowd\trleft-108\trgaph108\cellx2520\cellx9360 \pard\s2\sl240\intbl {\plain\f80\fs20 Load Zelt's Model\cell Use this to convert  velocity model in Zelt's ascii format into SeisWide binary format. This operation reverses an tool bar operation Save Velocity as.}\cell\row\pard\s2\sl240 \pard\s2\sl240 {\plain\f80\fs20 \par 
