{\plain\f16\fs20 
}{\plain\f80\fs20\b Display Seismic Sections\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f80\fs20 For a new Segy file, it is sometimes useful to run \'93 }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 View menu}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80\fs20 , Segy Info\'94 to display some of its header information.  If the numbers displayed as correct, it is most likely that this file can be used by SeisWide.\par 
\par 
In displaying the time section, near-offset stacked sections and wide-angle time sections are treated equally by the program.  However, for an MCS reflection profile, please make sure you have run the "Associate km to Trace" in the "Processing" menu before proceeding to display any segy data.  Keep in mind that SeisWide displays do not handle Segy data without information about distance or offsets in km.  \par 
\par 
For displaying a wide-angle data in model distance as opposed to offsets, you need to run \'93}{\ul {\f80\fs20 Define Source Position}}{\v menu_processing}{\plain\f80\fs20 \'94 to put the model distance in meters into the Segy header}{\plain\f80\fs20 .  Wide-angle time sections normally already have offsets in metres stored in the binary headers and therefore do not overwrite this information with "}{\ul {\f80\fs20 Associate km to Trace}}{\v menu_processing}{\plain\f80\fs20 ".\par 
\par 
To display a time section, select }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 View menu}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80\fs20 , Time Section, and a dialog box will appear. This dialog box is shared by various operations, and the same dialog box will be called when you choose to display}{\plain\f80\fs20\i  Depth Section, and Velocity Color Map}{\plain\f80\fs20 ., as well as some other processing routines.  You do not have to enter all the information in this dialog box before you can display something.  In fact, most of the information in this dialog box has defaults, and once you enter a file name for a time section, you may get your view right away even without entering any further information.\par 
\par 
You will soon be able to remember display parameters are divided into five groups.  To navigate through these groups, use the three tabs on top of the dialog box.\par 
}\par 
\pard\s2\li360\fi-360\sl240 {\plain\f80\fs20 }{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Common Parameters}{\plain\f80\fs20   include those that are common to most operations. }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Title of plot}{\plain\f80\fs20 : any text strings to be plotted on top of the plot. }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Shot1,shot2,shotstep}{\plain\f80\fs20 : the first trace, last trace, and increment of trace number for the display/plotting, default 0,10000,1 means including every trace within 0-10000. If not sure, just use the default values. Xmin,Xmax,Xtick fields represent the minimum, maximum distance in km for the plot, and the tick interval (Xtick in km). The Gain,Clip,MinAmp fields are the gain, clip (1 means that during area filling, the sample with a value equal the average amplitude will fill up the trace gap completely on the average.  If you know that the distances or offsets of your traces all increase with trace numbers, then check the last checkbox to enable the program to stop loading additional traces with it finds a trace not being displayed.  This action will not change the display at all; it just speeds up completion of tasks.\par 
}{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Time or Depth Sections: }{\plain\f80\fs20 includes three groups of parameters. The first is those for time sections only (including both zero-offset reflection, and wide-angle refraction sections).  click on  "Browse" to find a Segy file for a time section. Upon selection of file, the complete path and file name will be shown to the left of this "Browse" button.  (Note that if you leave the path as is, and save your document that contains these parameters, and later you move the corresponding Segy file, opening this document will not imply the program can find it; in that case, click "Browse" again to fix it.).  Tmin, Tmax, TTick specify the minimum, maximum time for display, and ticks. You can choose some trace header information to display: }{\plain\f80\fs20\i None, Trace Number,  FFID, CDP, or All.}{\plain\f80\fs20  This will display your selected trace information on top or bottom of the display, depending whether you are using face-down or face-up in the }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Common Parameters}{\plain\f80\fs20  group. Note that currently trace header information only displays well for traces with increasing distance/offsets; the program will not display this trace header information when it finds a trace that is to be placed to the left of any traces already on display. \par 
}{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20 The third group of parameters is for displaying  wide-angle time sections only, so do not change the default values of this group if you are displaying reflection data. Since Segy files do not discriminate between actual distance and offsets (i.e. distance and offsets are all stored at the same byte location in the Segy file), you need to tell the program here whether distance or offsets were written to the Segy header for wide-angle data. You could choose to display data as distance or offsets  For example, you are displaying a wide-angle data, and the Segy header is defined by "Offsets".  }{\plain\f80\fs20\b If you choose "Display as Distance", the program look for source positing in model distance in the Segy header, and add the distance of the source to the offsets for display. }{\plain\f80\fs20 Check "Variable Gain" to multiply the amplitudes by (range/XGain)^Power.  \par 
}{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20 The next group is for specifying depth information.  If you are only displaying a time section, skip this part completely. Zmin, Zmax, Ztick, dz are: Minimum and maximum depth for display and/or time-depth conversion; ZTick is the tick for depth; dz is only used for the conversion and can not be changed from here. \par 
}{\plain\f18\fs28 \'b7\tab }{\plain\f80\fs20\i Velocity Display}{\plain\f80\fs20 :  Specify here the information for velocity-color mapping schemes and for color-bar options. Note that you specify the coordinates of the upper-left corner, and the X-Y extent of the color bar by km.  The horizontal resolution of colors in km sets the horizontal mesh size for }{\plain\f80\fs20\ul linear}{\plain\f80\fs20  interpolation of velocities. Although you can use all the default values, you can choose one to six levels of velocity-color mapping schemes to tune up your needs.  In doing this, remember any color is specified by the red, green, and blue values between 0 and 255.  For example, 0, 0, 0 means a full darkness, 255, 0, 0 pure red, and 255, 255, 255 pure white.  Velocity Increment (in km/s) represents the color resolution for a corresponding velocity range; the colors within each layer will be gridded based on velocity at this interval.  Vmin, Vmid, Vmid2, Vmid3, Vmid4, Vmax are six velocity values whose corresponding Red, Green, Blue values will be used in the interpolation. }\par 
\pard\s2\sl240 {\plain\f80\fs20 \par 
Manipulating colors can be as complicated as a new profession, as somebody claims. In SeisWide, however, this is functionally simple and yet provides compatibility to most of your needs.  If you have a color scheme you like most (other than SeisWide\'92s default, e.g. a rainbow pattern), you can just first obtain the Red-Green-Blue values by using, for example, CorelDraw\'92s interactive color dialogs, then enter them into SeisWide\'92s color dialogs.  You then save your document into a new file, and whenever you want to use the same color scheme, you copy this file and open to see it.\par 
\par 
You can choose }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Edit menu}}{\v menu_edit}{\plain\f80\fs20 , Display Tune-up to tune-up your display, such as removing lables, OBS markers, model nodes et al..  \par 
