{\plain 
}{\plain Wide-angle Modeling\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 You can perform wide-angle modeling directly inside SeisWide software alone.  This includes interactive model editing, raytracing, and overlaying computed travel-time curves onto the seismogram display of your wide-angle data.  You can always compare this with coincident, if any, MCS reflection profile along the same line, by making a new .SEI document and selecting Window, Tile.  The MCS reflection profile will be converted to depth using your new velocity model to iterate a reasonable depth model.  \par 
\par 
Usually the first step for modeling a wide-angle data is to run }{\plain\f80\fs20 \'93Define Source Position\'94 to put the distance in meters into the Segy header.  See}{\plain\f80  }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Processing menu}}{\v menu_processing}{\plain\f80 .\par 
\par 
}{\plain\fs20 SeisWide invokes a separate program, called "myrayinvr.exe" and authored by Dr. Collin Zelt in 1992, to do the ray tracing.  You are advised to store all data for a particular line (or model) in one directory. myrayinvr.exe program needs a ray parameter file \'93.in\'94  and velocity model file \'93.bin\'94, both of which will be prompted when you do the ray-tracing.  Many of the information in the "r.in" file will not be useful for SeisWide, and in most cases, you will just duplicate this file from other lines and change the OBS positions (i.e. ishot and xshot in the .in file).  If you duplicate this file for another model, you'll just need to do a little extra work to change the axes specifications for X, Y, T.  \par 
\par 
It is usually a good idea to run \'93Check Model Integrety\'94 before running \'93Ray Tracing\'94 in the processing menu.  This guarantees that the model does not contain intersecting boundaries, whose existence may hang-up  the raytracing routine.  If any errors are detected, a NotePad document will be showed up in front of you.  You can inspect the causes and when no errors are found, proceed to the next step to do \'93Ray Tracing\'94. \par 
\par 
Selecting \'93Ray Tracing\'94 will pop up a dialog box for you to enter a .in file and a file for your velocity model (again you can use BROWSE to select files here).  On clicking OK, a window with black background will show up displaying the status of the ray tracing.  On Windows 95, a few information will be shown about the rays being traced. However on Windows NT 4.0, nothing is shown beside the black box and a status bar; This is caused by the in-appropriate display of fortran programs in Windows NT and you need not worry about this.  On finishing the ray tracing, you will be prompted to click OK to close the black window, followed by another click on OK to display seismic data with overlay of travel-time curves.  You may notice if you choose }{\uldb {\f80 View menu}}{\v menu_view}{\plain\f80 , }{\plain\f80\fs20 Time Section }{\plain\fs20 that }{\plain\f80\fs20 \'93Overlay Travel-time Curves\'94 in the \'93Time and Depth Sections\'94 tab is already checked automatically. \par 
\par 
Given there may be many travel-time curves for several OBS (in a single }{\plain\fs20 tx.out file)}{\plain\f80\fs20 , how SeisWide knows which ones to display?  Well, SeisWide }{\plain\fs20 looks in the }{\plain\fs20\b current directory}{\plain\fs20  (note: if you use BROWE to change directory, you change the current directory) for the file \'93tx.out\'94 generated by myrayinvr.exe for source information (defined by xshot in ray parameter file .in).  If it finds a source that matches the distance defined in the Segy header of your time section, the corresponding travel-time curves will be loaded and plotted.  So you must define the distance of source (using }{\uldb {\f80\fs20 Processing menu}}{\v menu_processing}{\plain\f80 , }{\plain\fs20 Define Source Position) before hand. \par 
\par 
A separate display of the all, or part of the raypaths can be obtained by running a DOS program "rayplot.bat" which will pop up on the full screen and at the same time generate a metafile "test.cgm" which can then be imported into your favorite graphics software (e.g. MS-Word, Excell, CorelDraw, or Lotus Freelance).  To do this, choose "Processing, Ray Trace" to perform the ray tracing first, copy the p.out file to your program installation directory, and run "rayplt.bat". The user is advised to print this raypath diagram frequently during the modeling processes to facilitate comparison with all information on the screen.}\par\page \pard\plain\s2\sl240 {\up $}{\footnote $ Window Arrange Icons Command}
